</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A7836CB196229417486FD76FB50FC2A" blockId="50.[212,1172,655,973]" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196229417486FD76FED4FD28" box="[212,278,695,719]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">Male.</emphasis>
(15) Scape missed. (16) Flagellum missed (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E196229417757FD77FC45FD29" box="[773,903,694,718]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="17.[144,211,1402,1424]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[144,1104,168,1370]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 10. Males of Megalopta. (A, C) Frontal view of head; (B, D) frontal view of flagellomeres; (A) M. purpurata Smith (holotype) from Tefé, Brazil; (B) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil; (C) M. yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (D) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (E) lateral view of sternum 4 of M. guarani sp. n. from Chapada dos Guimarães, Brazil; (F) posterolateral view of basal area of mesosoma M. guarani sp. n. from Chapada dos Guimarães, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm, except in E, scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004479" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004479/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">Figure 10A</figureCitation>
). (17) Metanotum with integument, in dorsal view, not hidden by short plumose pilosity (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E19622941779CFD17FB8CFD09" box="[974,1102,726,750]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[144,213,1405,1427]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[144,1104,168,1373]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 11. Males of Megalopta. (A, C, D). Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) M. karitiana sp. n. from Ouro Preto do Oeste, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (C) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (D) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (E) dorsal view of mesosoma of M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil; (F) posterior view of mesosoma of M. purpurata Smith (holotype) from Tefé, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004481/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">Figure 11F</figureCitation>
). (18) Basal area of metapostnotum blackish; its length less than half of metanotum (
<bibRefCitation id="4E564B3A196229417014FD37FECBFCC9" author="Moure JS" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" pagination="179 - 190" refId="ref30202" refString="Moure JS. 1958. On the species of Megalopta described by F. Smith (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). J N Y Entomol Soc. 66: 179 - 190." type="journal article" year="1958">Moure 1958</bibRefCitation>
); smooth, without rugulosities (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1962294176D1FCD7FCC5FCC9" box="[643,775,790,814]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="20.[212,279,1400,1422]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1368]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[212,1172,168,1368]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figure 12. Males of Megalopta. (A‒C) Habitus, dorsal view; (A) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (B) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil; (C) M. purpurata (holotype) Smith from Tefé, Brazil; (D‒F) posterolateral view of mesosoma; (D) M. yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (E) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (F) M. munduruku sp. n. from Belterra, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004483/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">Figure 12C</figureCitation>
). (19) Metepisternum with sparse pilosity, integument visible through pilosity; posterior upper margin of metepisternum unmodified, lacking a velvety process. (20). 1st and 2nd tarsomere of foreleg unobserved. (21) S3 with longitudinal sulcus, posterolateral margin notched. (22) S4 with medial protruding process, profile of process digitiform in lateral view; basal portion glabrous; posterolateral margin notched, notch not extending to basal half of sclerite.
</paragraph>
